ack to the group. We all sat around asking in group where he was to try and help. He didn't respond. We continued to watch his health decrease and then suddenly shoot back to full. He had LoH up and he sat on it and let me die. He killed whatever he was fighting and we all got exp (small consolation for the half bubble I'd just lost) and he returned. He then grumbled something about how he forgot he was grouped and that he wasted all the exp on us.<P>I degrouped him (after asking all the other members in tells if they didn't have a problem with that. They didn't).<P>The bottom line is that there are incompetent people out there and the only way they will ever learn is the hard way. Yes, it is sad that a member of a guild would do that but don't hold the poor actions of a person over the head of a whole guild.<P>My 2cp...<P>------------------<BR>Boanerges Thundercry<BR>Erudite Vicar of Prexus<BR>Proud member of <A HREF="http://www.steel-wind.com" TARGET=_blank>The Steel Wind</A><BR>Cazic Thule Server</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">tailchaser</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Personally, I'd just keep your eyes open for this other person, and refuse to join group that he's in.  I don't know what a letter to his guildmaster will accomplish, honestly.<P>I bring this up because I'm the guildmaster of a smallish guild myself.  Out of the blue one day, someone sent me a tell, claiming that someone in my guild was killstealing in Highpass and I need to make her stop.  I politely told him that being guildmaster makes me neither a babysitter nor a cop, and that I'm a dozen zones away, and if he has a problem with someone in my guild then he should talk to her and work it out with her.  I don't quite know what he expected me to do - tell my guildmate "I'm ordering you to leave the zone!"?  <P>   And yes, I did ask my guildmate her side, and she said that there were 2 groups at the Highpass zone killin